Food Debt to European Inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, the price was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British, and Canadian central bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the leitzins. In its discretion, the interest rate cut would favor the rise in commodity prices and the slight decrease in unemployment the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB is striving to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a slump: inflation needs to be “agreed” in order to rule out the need for further action.
At 3.3 per cent, inflation in Germany reached a 12-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
The rise in inflation in the euro area is due to the rise in food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat prices rose by 88 percent, and soybean prices also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in the price of edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but in 2009 it is expected to fall to 1.9 per cent.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3 percent inflation rate, but the average annual rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
