In many places, disinfectants are saved
More than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the containment of infections, according to the leading doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but shortly after, the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not be carried out since due to the bacterium that is still in the patient's body.
By December 10 of this year, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens from hospitals were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, a senior physician at the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been safely registered in hospitals, but the dark figure is expected to be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their noses without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin inflammation, or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are overdosed or used improperly, antibiotic-resistant bacteria arise from the well-responsive bacteria, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently malfunctioning immune system, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the hospital's daily routine.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, advised Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA there is only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the caregivers wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are examined for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for curbing the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients who have been admitted and isolate MRSA-infected immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not practiced as often in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance fund for this study.
Most cases will therefore only come to light if the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the Epidemiology Center.
On the part of the European Union, there are strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and disease images.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological tests are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can be formed, but this directive is also not always respected by hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer among outpatients, or patients in basic care, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Savings on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by caregivers.
This is why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted through droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are even often crowded, the beds barely lined, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the less financially well-off hospitals, there are even savings in disinfectants, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that directly favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
MRSA infections are a huge cost to health insurance companies, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
According to first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) as one of its priorities, as well as the prevention of infections in hospitals.
