Fodor and the Hungarian Six Percentage
As Environment Minister G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing Bali’s roadmap, which sets out emission reduction measures for the post-2012 period, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
At the moment, a fierce debate between industrialized and developing countries is underway.
The US has already signalled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be ready to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question at the conference is whether the developed countries are ready to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on the support of developing countries was also reached.
The Kyoto Protocol Adaptation Fund is to be managed by a 16-member council, presumably at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as reflected in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of the Environment G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by the 1990 values), regardless of whether the "Agreement after 2012" will be achieved successfully or not. The Union would even be willing to commit to a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrialized countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to commit to their commitments.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor stressed that the target of the countries that acceded to the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 per cent, while the EU had already committed itself with its 15 member states to a decrease of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will meet, as stated in the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
The commitment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement has to be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new, international emission reduction system, the most important of which is known to the IPCC, the UNFCCC and its international partners.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and an increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
