Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analyzing Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the “Movement for a Better Hungary”, have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things: In the context of the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy populations in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic discrimination in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such an argument, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure by the political leaders: "Persons of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups, who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition".
It is suspected that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremes, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the domestic and foreign media, "seriously damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember that since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has been continuously on the rise, so that since the summer of 2007 several organizations called "national self-defense associations" have been established.
"These groups have in common that they define themselves as a civilian organization, while they openly brag about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defense tasks (disaster protection, national defense, law enforcement), citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, the state itself."
And further: all this is done according to that method which tries to disguise various political aspirations as bourgeois initiative, based on the political and party intolerance of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association are therefore not only used to circumvent legal obstacles that could arise in the course of registration in court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-increasing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
