Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so the practice of rearranging the working days around the holidays has now become established, but next year will provide us with fewer such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood under "Holidays".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and non-working days.
Unemployed days are usually ecclesial holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate the New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are days off work - the latter alone so that the New Year's celebrants can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The national holidays are March 15, which commemorates the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, the commemoration day of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20, the founding of the state, on May 1, the work is celebrated, on November 1 and 2, we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of “workday shift” has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
However, the price of the extended weekends is that we have to work very well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holidays, is to be finalized, the Minister of Labour has for many years been set out in his own regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, public servants and civil servants alike.
Only companies and facilities where the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays, are excluded.
Today, the working order is only slightly confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24th, life in this country will formally stand still, since most of the days between Christmas and New Year's equilibrium, or the holiday specifically cancelled for this purpose, will take time off.
Next year, there will be more holidays in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer redundancies on working days than this year.
The calendar is first put on the head around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a day of rest.
The second redeployment is related to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th, you will have to work in advance on Friday, October 24th.
However, the end of the year will be completely in the sign of the holidays, after December 24th everything will lie and stand still, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six scary little things to annoy co-workers
Emails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we don't notice anymore: they bring "color" into everyday life at work.
