The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of the United Kingdom, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
In this way, more than $100 billion will be auctioned off in the currency markets.
At these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to lend money to each other.
For example, the US Fed sends $40 billion to auction, another 24 makes it easy for the European and Swiss central bank.
It is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of each country have agreed on such a coordinated approach to deter or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties facing the economy, i.e. the growing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in a report to his clients.
“Coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a U.S. recession from 65 percent to about 50 percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion in unused loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are still expecting billions of dollars in losses.
“Central banks must have been really afraid of what could still happen when they decided to do so,” said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
“It looks like the situation is really bad,” he continued.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession, possibly with an impact on economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank interest rate used for lending money between banks.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid to lend each other money, even though the central banks of the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
“This will have the same effect as further interest rate cuts,” Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
