At the time of the Spaniards, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana was once a warehouse or transit warehouse of treasures that the Spaniards had looted in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was founded at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the heads of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during prohibition) was liked and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were, among other things,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rises grew, cars drove across the wide boulevards, which were among the cult symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojimar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of the show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
What about today?
On the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana you can also leave your autograph.
Cocktails can be mixed at the bar of the Hotel Nacional.
