Debt grows
Government debt stems from government debt and is mainly due to the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
The public debt is financed by treasury orders, government bonds, direct bonds or, for example, by bonds of the European Investment Bank.
Domestic government debt has risen to SEK 719.4 billion this year.
The state’s foreign debt has now increased by 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable government debt reached SEK 803.3 billion at the end of September and decreased by SEK 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of government debt rose to 6.5 years.
Overall debt rose 13 percent over the year from the first to the third quarter, which is really a lot given how well the economy is doing.
Interestingly, the increase is particularly evident in debt securities, where the increase is 20 percent.
It’s bad that debts are rising, but on the other hand, this shows that you can do something before the pension reform comes,” Pikora commented on the data.
Better than expected
The financing strategy and the handling of government debt for 2007 shows that the government had planned to raise 159.2 billion crowns for this year.
At the beginning of December, however, the Ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion crowns thanks to the better development of the state budget policy.
This amount stems mainly from the government budget deficit, which this year will obviously reach 76 billion crowns instead of the estimated 91.3 billion.
It also includes a maximum of SEK 13.3 billion for the Consolidation Agency, a ten-billion reserve to pay pensions, the financing of government debt securities of SEK 43 billion and rates for bonds with the European Investment Bank of SEK 1.8 billion.
