End of mediation on 10 December
The intermediaries of the Troika, which unites the European Union, the United States and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the 90% Albanian-speaking province could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, constituted the sixth and last negotiating meeting since the troika had received the mandate for a new mediation from the UN last August.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked the granting of Kosovo's independence to the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this end date.
Russia has been and continues to be an advocate of a negotiated solution, an amicable solution, Botsane-Khartchenko said.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After Kosovo has been under UN administration for eight years, the Western countries hold independence under EU supervision for the only solution with a future.
