He went on to say that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to start negotiations immediately to find a final settlement of the 60-year-old disputes between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do anything to help them conclude a peace treaty before the end of 2008.
Meanwhile, the Palestinians must destroy the terrorist infrastructure and Israel must stop its colonization work, Bush said, reminding both parties of their commitments to the peace roadmap they had agreed to in 2003.
The head of the White House stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority under Abbas ultimately seek a peace treaty that aims to clarify all open issues without exception, including the central issues.
This term encompasses the three serious problems that the disputes between Israelis and Palestinians mainly revolve around: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of the Arab refugees who were expelled from their homeland in the course of the 1948 conflict, which is in the present-day state of Israel.
According to the American president, Abbas took the floor and insisted that the upcoming negotiations be conducted comprehensively and thoroughly and provide a settlement for all points, including Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, water and security.
When Olmert, for his part, took the floor, he pledged that the upcoming ceasefire negotiations would be conducted directly and without interruption, and that he would make every effort to ensure that they could be concluded before the end of 2008.
Bush has set the deadline for implementing his vision of two states, one Palestinian and one Israeli, which stand side by side, for the end of 2008.
Saudi Arabia has revealed that it received assurances in this sense from Bush before it decided to participate in the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a great success for Washington, has led to a plan adopted by all Arab countries that offers Israel peace, in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis represents a dividing line in the history of the Middle East, especially because it attacks the roots of the conflict and its central points of view, the Saudi Arabian prince says in his interview with the Saudi-funded Arabic-language daily newspaper.
