Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) will need more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector, which is indispensable for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that, due to its duration, the distance of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools provided by the astronauts to carry out the repair, has achieved several records.
The problem occurred on Wednesday, when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the Space Shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part that will soon take up the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module laboratories.
But you have to be able to power them.
The crew’s second task, therefore, was to implement a 17.5-tonne solar-powered module that was already on the ISS to bring it to its final position.
After moving it, the crew decided to restructure the solar panels of the module, whose span is 76 meters.
And in doing so, it happened that one of the collectors that can be folded up like accordions was damaged by a clamped cable at a length of about one meter.
The restructuring was halted to prevent further damage to the collector.
The astronauts, who originally left the Discovery spacecraft for a control flight and then repaired another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to dedicate themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was selected to walk around at the end of the 30-metre-long remote-controlled arm of the spacecraft that had been attached to the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Large, resistant, very skilful, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
So, the 46-year-old learned doctor was selected to operate the injured solar collector.
After carefully examining the damage, he severed the faulty cable and fixed some kind of rail on the damaged spot.
He was supported by a second spacewalker who remained near the lock, and, from the inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, wrapped up a mini hockey racket, with insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar collectors, which generate several hundred volts, the astronauts on board the station had invented and crafted.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector had fully folded up before counting his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed a half-day of relaxation, before today seven astronauts returned to the Discovery spacecraft to presumably begin the return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
