A heavy memory
After being treated confidentially for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed on a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be accessed until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, that is, individual and name-related, that is, at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
In May 2006, the 11 states in charge of its administration – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
After the process of ratification of this Decision has been completed, the opening is valid since yesterday.
Heikle Information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will allow for research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the health status of forced laborers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The prisoner lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal requests.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
Nothing fundamentally new can be expected in these documents, explained Prof. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
