Following numerous rumors regarding the creation of a new music festival in Philadelphia by C3 Presents, the promoter/producer announces the Vineland Music Festival in New Jersey, in collaboration with Festival Republic of British producer Melvin Benn.
It’s an honor for our company to work with a person who has served, no more and no less, as a model for the current festival movement in America,” Charlie Jones of C3 said on Bilboard.com.
C3 hosts the Lollapalooza Festival in Chicago and the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
Vineland, New Jersey, is a summer destination for camping holidays.
The festival will probably take place from August 8-10 on a 500-acre private farm about 40 minutes from Philadelphia.
Festival Republic head Melvin Benn, formerly known as Mean Fiddler, is one of the producers of the most prestigious festivals in the world.
In 1989, he took over the leadership of the Reading Festival in the United Kingdom, which attracts around 80,000 people annually.
In 1999, Melvin Benn added the Leeds Festival to his portfolio, and then, in 2006, Festival Republic created the Latitude Festival at Henham Park in Suffolk.
Since 2002, Melvin Benn, as co-owner, has also been responsible for the production, licensing and organisational tasks of the Glastonbury Festival, which can now accommodate up to 177,500 people.
Charlie Jones of C3, who describes Glastonbury as the most inspiring event he’s ever been to, says his company and Melvin Benn’s are working side by side to provide the area with a European-style festival event.
We have chosen Philadelphia as a market and are working diligently with the Fairmount Park Commission to create a festival in downtown Philadelphia, says Charlie Jones.
We were negotiating mt the city and the commission was motivated and excited about this project.
“Unfortunately, we have been stuck in policy debates regarding the current administration,” continues Charlie Jones.
"Fortunately, we were able to discuss with Melvin Benn and we are preparing to create a great festival in an extraordinary place that will ultimately benefit the population."
C3 Presents has revived the 2005 Lollapalooza Festival in Grand Park Chicago after it joined the Austin City Limits Music Festival in 2002.
The two events were able to achieve $9.8 million and $11.8 million in gross tax days in 2007.
These two festivals take place in an urban setting.
“Melvin Benn’s European model is a rural festival, while ours is more likely to take place on urban green spaces,” says Charlie Jones.
"The goal is to somehow merge these two concepts together, to convey at the same time the impression of a rural festival in the European and an urban one in the American way."
Vineland is about halfway between Philadelphia and Atlantic City.
“The community of Vineland, including the mayor, is taking on the burden of this event with joy,” says Charlie Jones.
The latter refuses to disclose the terms of the agreement, but he confirms that "they are interesting enough to invest in such an event and host a festival that will hopefully have a long life."
Charlie Jones says the festival’s recording capacity is “very large,” corresponding to about 80,000 people at the Bonnaroo Music Festival in Tennessee.
He says the invitations were sent to the groups, but that nothing could be confirmed when they were printed.
“Vineland will offer tasteful rock, but the music will be very diverse, hoping to attract all kinds of spectators,” says Charlie Jones.
His C3 partners, who received the Top Independent Promoter Award from the last Bollboard Touring Award, are Charlie Walker and Charles Attal.
