Congress approves the MIFID directive, which entered into force on November 1.
In parallel with the parliamentary drafting that ended today with the Congressional decision in the Senate on the additional/amendment proposals associated with the project, the government published the provisions resulting from the new law with the intention of allowing the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of the congressional and senate deputies, who in their negotiations and votes had pursued the goal of establishing the best possible regulation, which ensures the safety of investors and regulates the individual entrepreneurial activities in order to guarantee a generally more efficient market.
In addition to modernising financial markets, the MIFID, which re-defines the Securities Services Regulation, seeks to improve investor protection, increase the control claim of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive allows for the provision of financial advice to both specialised firms and to natural or legal persons, and also contributes to the creation of new financial services companies (ESIS) to the advisory firms that merge with investment and securities brokerage companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions, so that the multilateral systems of securities transactions and the systems for the internationalisation of trade orders are added to the regulated circulation markets, which would eventually compete with the current economic actors.
The law obliges investment firms to register the focus of their company profile, the confrontation and forms of risk management in the market, and all completed projects, in order to facilitate the CNMV’s control task.
The Congressional Economic Commission envisioned further changes in retrospect, with the decision that the securitized debt securities must now be considered complex financial assets for the investor due to their high level of risk, confirmed by the US mortgage and banking crisis.
In addition, the Directive on the legal restriction of the fields of work of qualified economists came into force 30 years after 1977, when the Regulation restricting the fields of work reserved for economic scientists was adopted.
The Senate, for its part, established new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the economic mediator, who works on behalf of others, does not need authorization from the CNMV and can offer its services for the commercialization of products and for customer acquisition at the same time to several investment companies.
The Harmonised Index of Consumer Prices (HICP) rose by five-tenths in November and is now at 4.1%.
The indicator used by Eurostat to assess the inflation rate within the European Union provides the average price development in Spain in November.
Its publication is in line with the principles of Eurostat and the European Central Bank (ECB), which aim at a local and quality comparison with US products by disclosing the data.
The forecast for the indicator can be prepared prematurely using the same approach as for the harmonised consumer price index, but at the same time using various other statistical modelling methods to estimate the information not available at the time of calculation.
However, the Spanish Statistical Office (INE) cautioned that the pre-determined indicator should serve only as a guide value, and therefore should not be consistent with the final result announced on 14 December.
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) will remain at a relatively high level
