New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is brewing between Ukraine and Russia, raising the risk that Russian fuel exports to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of Russia’s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine, and any dispute between the two nations is monitored very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to the EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned Gazprom gas monopoly are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom’s imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," Anatoli Kinakh, Ukraine's economic minister, told Reuters.
“The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.”
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut deliveries to Ukraine.
This led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drastically pushed prices up.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom replenishes its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
