Losses and losses are still low.
According to the rating agency Moody, the third-quarter slump rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in U.S. private insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt fall in bankruptcy filings, which in turn accounted for a large portion of card losses; the number of filings (and thus the bailout fees) would rise again, whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate or not.
Industry also reports solid payment rates that show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stagnation in other corners of structured financing.
