Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind swirls at the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the proof - it detected electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus shoots at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous “supply theory”, lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the devil’s twin on Earth, but it’s a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has struck such a completely different evolution, is the basic question of the ESA mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as no probe has been on the way to explore this planet since the early 1990s.
The latest research findings, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underscore the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, according to the researchers.
“They also show that our neighboring planet’s commonalities with Earth are larger than initially thought,” ESA said in a statement.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud swirl at the South Pole that rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-inner planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
However, it revolves much more slowly around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus is barely reminiscent of Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets originated under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on Venus was lost in space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
