These aren't Warhol's crates.
Those who combine the terms Sweden and wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Isn't that right?
Currently, manufactured wooden crates in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's work directory.
Most of the ninety-four "Typ Stockholm" brillo boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago further aroused doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of 1968, internal research at the Moderna Museum in Stockholm now comes to a sobering result: the six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director of the Umm Musek Veret dem Hultén
The prehistory is intertwined, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these did not come (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
These were not works of art, but examples of them, mere exhibits.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol probably granted permission to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museum.
Contemporaries now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at the time were authorized as original Andy-Warhol-Brillo boxes with the name "Typ Stockholm" rightly entered the art and auction history.
Some of them have raised more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that about a hundred wooden crates were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator at the Moderna Museet, has also studied three privately owned brillo boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press span plates were first primed and smeared, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the pressing chipboard with a paint roller without primer - in addition, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museum, Lars Nittve, "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion than the Moderna Museum's collection material will be the six copies in the boxes."
As early as July, however, the Authentication Board announced it would follow up on the “severe allegations” made regarding the soap powder boxes.
But since then, they have been hiding in unrelenting silence.
Rebel soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers have abandoned their positions at a hotel in Manila, demanding the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He cannot be held responsible for bloodshed, Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and election fraud, told reporters at the hotel.
Government loyalists had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas.
About two dozen soldiers had surrounded themselves in the building for hours.
About half of them were in court on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the trial to suddenly settle down with about 30 sympathizers.
The military policemen who were supposed to guard him had apparently run over to him and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government troops cordoned off the district around the noble hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People have had enough,” said Trillanes.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who previously commanded the Scout Rangers’ elite unit, said other army units wanted to join the march soon.
Critics of the government had called for large demonstrations against the president for Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed by accusations of corruption for months.
Manila's financial district was the main scene of attempted mutiny against Arroyo in 2003.
The insurrection failed after almost 24 hours of the army's refusal to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
